huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This unit is a General Season hunt unit and is not managed to be a trophy unit but every year a few really nice bucks are taken.  Hunters should be aware of the private property and learn the boundaries. There are many areas within this unit that you can get away from the roads and other hunters.  Deer are naturally more abundant in these areas.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: Hunters that go into these areas should prepare for every weather condition and little to no cell phone coverage.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for hot & dry, or rainy, lightning, windy or even snowy conditions.  Early snow storms occur often during this hunt.  Most of the time snow will melt off within a day or so.  Be prepared for muddy or snowy road conditions.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Migration Patterns: Deer on this unit move down in elevation for the winter and they winter primarily on State, Federal and Private Lands and on south facing slopes at lower elevation.

Mule Deer rut: The mule deer rut usually runs from mid Nov.-mid Dec. so it does not affect this hunt.

Recommended areas on the Beaver Unit: There are numerous suggested areas to hunt on this unit.

Early in the season deer can be found in the large meadows or parks. Deer on the archery hunt are found at higher elevation. As hunting pressure persists deer move into the thicker cover. If you choose to hunt the high country, be prepared for unpredictable weather and lots of rocks.

During the hunts most of the deer on the unit are found in the habitat belt where aspen mixes with sagebrush and conifer. That zone across the Beaver is the most productive for deer. Every canyon across the Beaver has deer and they are of similar quality.

The suggested areas to hunt include (starting on the west side of the unit):
Big Johns Flat- Plenty of Access and camping
Big Flat- Plenty of access and camping
Kents Lake- Popular camping area must hike off the road to get away from people
Rainbow Mine- Limited road access
Cottonwood Creek- limited road access
City Creek Peak - limited road access, popular area
Lebaron Reservoir- limited road access, popular area
Mumford Resevoir – Limited access, steep areas
Bakers Canyon - popular area
Briggs Ridge – remote hunting area, steep terrain
Shingle Creek Meadows- Some ATV trails and remote hunting opportunities.
North Creek – Limited Access
Manderfield- gravel roads, a little flatter area, be aware of private Property

huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Beaver, Garfield, Iron, Millard, Piute and Sevier counties—Boundary begins at SR-130 and I-15; north on SR-130 to SR-21; north on SR-21 to SR-257; north on SR-257 to Black Rock Road; east on this road to I-15; south on I-15 to I-70; east on I-70 to US-89; south on US-89 to SR-20; west on SR-20 to I-15; south on I-15 to SR-130. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Beaver, Cedar City, Panguitch, Richfield. Boundary Questions?  Call the Cedar City office, 435-865-6100.
